{"id":14881503,"mediaExerciseId":"b03f3536-f1f3-4ae0-92b4-8fde09fe55bd","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"15","chapterTitle":"Raising Capital","groupId":612403,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":529,"solutions":[{"id":6019175,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to assess the debt and equity offering size. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/d9b864e5571f0a7463bf37569aa7c858/lateximg_large.png","width":952},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/d9b864e5571f0a7463bf37569aa7c858/lateximg.png","width":476}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A **debt offering** occurs when a firm generates funds by issuing debt securities to investors. This offers funds on the stipulation that it be returned with interest.\n\n\nAn **equity offering** is a public selling of a firm's equity to generate finance. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":175,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/c1b82ecb273b42b208f5eab4be0f40af/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":88,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/c1b82ecb273b42b208f5eab4be0f40af/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**Since stockholders take on greater risk when acquiring securities than a firm's bond, debt offers are more common**. When a firm prefers debt over equity investment, it does not lose ownership, as with equity investment. A minimal debt proportion is seen positively by creditors, which advantages the firm if it needs to secure further debt funding in the future.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/8a96dee2d8f7895914b655d543ad70a4/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/8a96dee2d8f7895914b655d543ad70a4/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Since large firms have the most accessibility to public financial markets, debt financing is larger than equity financing. On the other hand, small firms usually face equity concerns when they go public.\n\nBorrowing does not give an ownership interest; hence, it does not reduce the equity investment of the firm's shareholders. **If the firm is continuously developing, debt may be a less costly option for additional investment.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":216,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/1372bea575c6089cd2e53109948cb66d/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":110,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/14/333d3b964487f1e917a9f97dc2c6bb2d/1372bea575c6089cd2e53109948cb66d/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"e5424d72-c9ac-47d6-a7f9-7e952437464f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition"